# VPS operations: connect and execute directly

For ANY VPS / production task (deploy, reset, inspect logs, edit `.env`, run
DB queries, restart containers), connect over SSH and run the commands
yourself. Do NOT hand the user a command list to run manually.

- SSH alias: `ai-hot-news-prod` (`ssh ai-hot-news-prod '<cmd>'`)
- Project dir: `/opt/ai-signal` · compose project: `ai-signal`
- Containers: `ai-signal-web-1`, `ai-signal-worker-1`, `ai-signal-db-1`

## Permission facts (login user `deploy`)

- In the `docker` group (so `docker ...` works) but has **no `sudo`**.
- `/opt/ai-signal` dir is NOT writable by `deploy`; `.env` is owned by `deploy`
  mode 600. Edit `.env` via `/tmp` then truncate-write the owned file:
  `sed '...' .env > /tmp/e && cat /tmp/e > .env`. To touch a root-owned file,
  use a throwaway root container: `docker run --rm --user 0 -v /opt/ai-signal:/work busybox sh -c '...'`.
- `docker compose` reads `.env`, so it only works while `deploy` can read it.
- Run DB / one-off scripts via the running container, e.g.
  `docker exec ai-signal-db-1 psql -U aisignal -d aisignal -c "..."`,
  `docker exec -e RESET_CONFIRM=yes ai-signal-worker-1 npm run reset-corpus`.

## Still confirm first

Before destructive/irreversible prod actions (wiping the corpus, dropping data,
force-recreating), state what you're about to do and get a quick OK — then run
it yourself. Don't make the user perform the SSH steps.
